PY  - 1997
Y1  - 1997/05/01
DO  - 10.1162/003355397555299
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 112
IS  - 2
SP  - 581
EP  - 602
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - The paper examines the evolutionary foundations of bilateral bargaining behavior. Interaction is assumed to be personal, in the sense that agents may recognize each others' bargaining strategies. In particular, the model allows interaction between “obstinate” agents, whose demands are independent of the opponent, and “sophisticated” agents, who adapt to their opponent's expected play. When the pie's size is certain, evolution favors obstinate agents who insist on getting at least half the pie. The unique outcome is an equal split. In sufficiently noisy environments, sophisticated behavior appears in equilibrium together with greedy obstinate behavior. There is then a positive probability of conflict.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1162/003355397555299
ER  - 



